rel=3D\"inline\">Tooth Whitening</a></li> =0A    </ul> =0A\t\t=0A\t</div> =0A=\n\t<!-- END: div Cols -->=0A\t=0A\t</div>=0A\t<!-- END: div learn -->=0A\t=0A\t</d=\niv> =0A\t<!-- END: div LearnWrapper -->=0A=0A\t<!-- BEGIN: DetailWrapper -->=\n=0A\t<div id=3D\"DetailWrapper\">=0A=0A\t<!-- This is where you put in the info=\nrmation and images for each item -->=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Amalgam\" style=3D\"di=\nsplay: none;\">=0A\t\t<img src=3D\"_images/procedure_06Before.jpg\" width=3D\"248=\n\" height=3D\"175\" />=0A\t\t<p>Dental amalgam fillings, or silver fillings, hav=\ne been used by dentists for more than 150 years. They are relatively long-l=\nasting and inexpensive and have been used to restore teeth in more than 100=\n million Americans. Amalgam fillings contain a mixture of silver, copper, m=\nercury, and tin. The mercury, one of the few metals which is a liquid at ro=\nom temperature, renders the other strengthening metals malleable so the den=\ntist can shape the filling into the prepared cavity.</p>=0A\t\t<p>Dental amal=\ngam has an indisputable safety record and has been extensively reviewed. Th=\ne U.S. Public Health Service issued a report in 1993 stating there is no he=\nalth reason not to use amalgam, except in the extremely rare case of the pa=\ntient who is allergic to a component of amalgam. This supports the finding =\nof the FDA, the National Institute of Health Technology Assessment Conferen=\nce, and the National Institute of Dental Research that dental amalgam is a =\nsafe and effective restorative material. The current debate regarding amalg=\nam has more to do with the impact that the disposal of the excess filling m=\naterial may have on the environment, than its safety for use in humans.</p>=\n=0A\t\t<p>Mercury, in large doses, can be toxic. The majority of mercury that=\n enters our bodies comes from food (seafood), water, and air. In fact the m=\nost directly toxic form of mercury is organic mercury, such as that found i=\nn fish. The World Health Organization (WHO) has estimated that eating seafo=\nod once a week raises the amount of mercury in the urine 2-8 times the leve=\nl from the placement of an amalgam filling. You would need to have 200 amal=\ngam fillings placed every day or eat 25-100 servings of fish every day to r=\neach a toxic level of mercury. For a recent article from WebMD about the sa=\nfety of amalgam fillings, please click here.</p>=0A\t\t<p>Because of structur=\nal and esthetic reasons, however, Dr. Boyd may choose not to place an amalg=\nam filling. Gold fillings are usually the strongest and porcelain or compos=\nite fillings are the most esthetic. If you would like to have your silver f=\nillings replaced for any reason (esthetics etc.) or if they are defective, =\nDr. Boyd would be happy to remove them using techniques that reduce the amo=\nunt of mercury released upon removal. If you have any further questions, pl=\nease ask Dr. Boyd.</p>=0A\t</div>=0A=0A\t<div id=3D\"Antibiotic\" style=3D\"disp=\nlay: none;\">=0A\t\t<p>Patients with certain preexisting conditions may requir=\ne \"antibiotic prophylaxis.\" This involves taking an antibiotic 1 hour befor=\ne certain dental treatments in order to prevent the possibility of bacteria=\n growing on the valves of the heart, known as \"bacterial endocarditis.\" If =\nyou have a condition (listed below) which requires antibiotic prophylaxis o=\nr think you may, Dr. Boyd may confer with your physician on how best to man=\nage your particular situation.</p>=0A        <p>To learn more about antibio=\ntic prophylaxis and the links between dental health and heart disease, clic=\nk here http://www.americanheart.org/presenter.jhtml?identifier=3D3047083 to=\n visit the American Heart Association's web page. </p>=0A<p>According to Am=\nerican College of Cardiology and the American Heart Association guidelines,=\n Antibiotic prophylaxis with dental procedures is reasonable only for patie=\nnts with cardiac conditions associated with the highest risk of adverse out=\ncomes from endocarditis, including:</p>=0A=0A<p>&bull;Prosthetic cardiac va=\nlve or prosthetic material used in valve repair</p>=0A<p>&bull;Previous bac=\nterial endocarditis</p>=0A<p>Congenital heart disease only in the following=\n categories:</p>=0A<p>&bull;Unrepaired cyanotic congenital heart disease, i=\nncluding those with palliative shunts and conduits</p>=0A<p>&bull;Completel=\ny repaired congenital heart disease with prosthetic material or device, whe=\nther placed by surgery or catheter intervention, during the first six month=\ns after the procedure</p>=0A<p>&bull;Repaired congenital heart disease with=\n residual defects at the site or adjacent to the site of a prosthetic patch=\n or prosthetic device (which inhibit endothelialization)</p>=0A<p>&bull;Car=\ndiac transplantation recipients with cardiac valvular disease</p>=0A=0A=0A\t=\n</div>=0A\t=0A    <div id=3D\"Arestin\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A\t\t<p>AREST=\nIN=C2=AE (minocycline hydrochloride) is an effective antibiotic treatment i=\nn treating periodontal (gum) disease. It comes in a powder form that is eas=\nily placed inside infected periodontal pockets just after the dental profes=\nsional finishes the scaling and root planing (SRP) procedure.</p>=0A        =\n=0A<p>ARESTIN contains \"Microspheres\"-tiny, bead-like particles that are sm=\naller than grains of sand not visible to the eye. The Microspheres are fill=\ned with the antibiotic minocycline, and they release the drug over time int=\no the infected periodontal pocket, killing bacteria that live there for up =\nto 21 days.</p>=0A=0A<p>ARESTIN Microspheres continue to fight the infectio=\nn for up to 21 days after SRP. In clinical studies, ARESTIN has been proven=\n to be more effective than using SRP alone. ARESTIN also significantly redu=\nced the size of periodontal pockets compared to SRP alone, killed the bacte=\nria most commonly associated with periodontal disease, and reduced bleeding=\n on probing of the gums.</p>=0A\t</div>=0A    =0A\t<div id=3D\"Bridges\" style=\n=3D\"display: none;\">=0A\t\t<p>When a tooth is missing, one option to replace =\nit is a bridge. A bridge fills the space between two (or more) teeth by sus=\npending a \"fake\" tooth (or teeth) between the crowns. This necessitates pre=\nparing some teeth on either side of the space.</p>=0A        <p> Usually a =\nbridge is made out of porcelain that has been fused onto metal (gold). This=\n enables the dentist to imitate the color and shape of the surrounding teet=\nh. Click here for a picture. </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"BrushingTechn=\nique\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A    \t\t<img src=3D\"_images/brushing.jpg\" w=\nidth=3D\"245\" height=3D\"175\" />=0A=0A\t\t<p>Make sure you are brushing with a =\nSOFT nylon toothbrush.</p>=0A        <p>&bull;Wet and apply toothpaste. The=\n toothpaste companies love to advertise huge ribbons of toothpaste on tooth=\nbrushes, but only a pea-sized amount is necessary.</p>=0A            <p>&bu=\nll;Hold your toothbrush at a 45-degree angle to the teeth so that the brist=\nles of the brush aim at and under the gums. Move the brush in small circles=\n, gently massaging the gums and teeth.</p>=0A\t\t\t<p>&bull;You may use more v=\nigorous back and forth motions for the biting surfaces of your teeth.</p>=\n=0A            <p>&bull;In order to avoid abrasion of the outside surfaces =\nof the teeth, start your brushing on the inside of the lower teeth. This is=\n especially beneficial since the majority of calculus (tartar) accumulates =\nthere.</p>=0A            <p>&bull;Don't forget to brush your tongue, either=\n with your toothbrush or a specially designed tongue-scraper. Bacteria love=\n to colonize the back of the tongue.</p>=0A            <p>&bull;The entire =\nprocess should last about 2 minutes.</p>=0A=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Com=\nposite\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A\t\t<p>Composite (or bonding) is a kind o=\nf tooth-colored plastic material which is applied to a tooth in a soft stat=\ne and is then hardened by a light or laser.</p>=0A        <p> While this is=\n an excellent material for smaller cavities, small chips (fractures), or sp=\naces, larger cavities require materials that are stronger, such as gold or =\nporcelain.</p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Cosmetic\" style=3D\"display: none=\n;\">=0A\t\t<img src=3D\"_images/procedure_10After.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"=\n120\" />=0A\t\t<p>Cosmetic dentistry is the art of improving a smile through p=\nrocedures like bleaching (tooth whitening), orthodontics (Invisalign=E2=84=\n=A2), porcelain veneers, porcelain inlay/onlays, composite fillings, bondin=\ng, gingival recontouring, bridges etc.</p>=0A        <p> If you are unhappy=\n with any aspect of your smile, please talk to Dr. Boyd. </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=\n=0A\t<div id=3D\"Crowns\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A    \t<img src=3D\"_images=\n/procedure_05Before.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"160\" />=0A\t\t<img src=3D\"_i=\nmages/procedure_05After.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"160\" />=0A=0A\t\t<p>When=\n the whole tooth needs to be restored, a crown is fabricated which replaces=\n all of the surfaces that can be seen in the mouth. Gold and porcelain can =\nbe used in these restorations. </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Dentures\" s=\ntyle=3D\"display: none;\">=0A\t\t<p>When all the teeth of one arch (upper or lo=\nwer) are missing, a complete denture can be made. Either acrylic or porcela=\nin teeth are held in an acrlyic base which covers the gums. Even though the=\n denture-wearing patient no longer has teeth and may be satisfied with the =\nperformance of the existing denture, regular check-ups with Dr. Boyd are re=\ncommended every six months. </p>=0A        <p>This is to ensure that the gu=\nms underneath the denture remain as healthy as possible and that problems c=\nan be identified as early as possible. If you are dissatisfied with the per=\nformance of your denture, speak to Dr. Boyd about the possibility of gettin=\ng implants to help secure the denture. </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Flo=\nssing\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A        \t<img src=3D\"_images/flossing.jp=\ng\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"175\" />=0A=0A\t\t<p>&bull;Break off about 12 inche=\ns of floss and wind it around the middle finger of each hand until only 4-6=\n inches of floss separates your fingers. </p>=0A\t<p>&bull;Holding the floss=\n tightly, guide the floss between your teeth without snapping it through. <=\n/p>=0A\t<p>&bull;Once the floss passes through where the two teeth contact, =\nallow the floss to curve against the neck of one tooth and then the other, =\nrubbing the tooth beneath the gums. </p>=0A\t<p>&bull;Remember: flossing mec=\nhanically removes plaque on the surfaces in between teeth that a toothbrush=\n can't reach. </p>=0A\t<p>&bull;Don't forget to get the back surface of the =\nlast teeth in the back. </p>=0A\t<p>&bull;If this is very difficult for you,=\n you might prefer another instrument to help you clean between your teeth, =\nsuch as a stimudent or interproximal brush. </p>=0A\t<p>Ask your hygienist i=\nn the office for more information. </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Fluorid=\ne\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A\t\t<p>Fluoride is a mineral that occurs natur=\nally in all water sources, even oceans. More than 50 years ago, a dentist i=\nn Texas noted that children in areas of naturally occuring fluoridated wate=\nr had fewer cavities. Since then, the ideal quantity of fluoride has been d=\netermined to be 0.7-1.2 parts per million. In an effort to take advantage o=\nf a very cost-effective means of reducing the occurence of cavities in chil=\ndren, local governances began regulating the amount of fluoride in their wa=\nter supplies. </p>=0A<p>Community water fluoridation has been hailed as one=\n of the greatest and most cost effective public health efforts ever achieve=\nd. For the price of a few cents per year per person, the occurence of cavit=\nies dropped 60% in children born in areas with treated water. Although fluo=\nride in a dose much higher than is in tap water can discolor teeth (fluoros=\nis) and in tremendously high doses can even be fatal (just as sodium or pot=\nassium are), its impact on dental health has been dramatic. </p>=0A<p>Patie=\nnts should be aware that although Manhattan and most of the surrounding are=\nas in New York and Connecticut have closely regulated, fluoridated water su=\npplies, parts of Long Island and most of New Jersey do not. Currently, New =\nJersey ranks 49th in the percentage of state populations that drink fluorid=\nated public water at the CDC=E2=80=99s recommended therapeutic level of one=\n part per million. Shockingly, 80 percent=E2=80=947.4 million New Jerseyans=\n=E2=80=94do not receive fluoridated water from the public drinking supplies=\n. </p>=0A<p>In order to check whether your home is receiving fluoridated wa=\nter, you can call your local governance, your local water supply company, o=\nr to search for New York counties, click <a href=3D\"http://apps.nccd.cdc.go=\nv/MWF/CountyDataV.asp?State=3DNY\">here</a>, for New Jersey click <a href=3D=\n\"http://yosemite.epa.gov/ogwdw/ccr.nsf/New+Jersey?OpenView\">here</a>, for C=\nonnecticut click <a href=3D\"http://www.ct.gov/dph/lib/dph/drinking_water/pd=\nf/fluor_list.pdf\">here</a>.</p>=0A=0A<p>Brita=E2=84=A2 water filtration sys=\ntems have been tested and verified to remove only a trace amount of fluorid=\ne over the life of a filter, so we recommend Brita water filtration systems=\n. Many brands of bottled water, however, do not contain the level of fluori=\nde recommended by the ADA. In fact, bottled water is not required to state =\nhow much fluoride is contained in it and may in fact contain none at all. <=\n/p>=0A<p>Along with the fluoride received in the drinking water, topical ap=\nplications of fluoride (like ACT Rinse) aid the body in rebuilding teeth al=\nready eaten away by small cavities. This is where fluoride in toothpaste an=\nd topical applications of fluoride in the dental office play a role especia=\nlly if you are not receiving fluoride from your local water supply or only =\ndrink bottled, non-fluoridated water. </p>=0A<p>In certain cases where pati=\nents have moderate to high risk of dental cavities, Dr. Boyd may write a pr=\nescription for a special toothpaste which has an even higher concentration =\nof fluoride.  This may help prevent the incidence of new cavities in your m=\nouth. </p>=0A\t</div>=0A    =0A    <div id=3D\"Fractured\" style=3D\"display: n=\none;\">=0A            <img src=3D\"_images/procedure_12Before.jpg\" width=3D\"2=\n48\" height=3D\"160\" />=0A            <img src=3D\"_images/procedure_12After.j=\npg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"160\" />=0A\t\t<p>Unlike teeth with obvious fractu=\nres, teeth with fractured tooth syndrome usually have fractures that are to=\no small to be seen on X-rays. Sometimes the fracture is below the gum line,=\n making it even more difficult to identify. People who grind or clench thei=\nr teeth may be more susceptible to cracked tooth syndrome because of the co=\nnstant forces put on their teeth. </p>=0A        <p>Sometimes a person's no=\nrmal bite causes certain molar cusps (the highest points of the tooth) to e=\nxert so much pressure on the opposing tooth that it cracks.  Back teeth wit=\nh large fillings or teeth that have undergone root canal treatment are weak=\ner than other teeth and may be more likely to crack. People with one cracke=\nd tooth are more likely to have others, either at the same time or in the f=\nuture. If the crack worsens, the fractured portion may become loose.</p>=0A=\n=0A<p>If you grind or clench your teeth, talk to your dentist about treatme=\nnt. Grinding can increase your risk of cracked tooth syndrome.  A night gua=\nrd may help prevent further damage.</p>=0A=0A<p>Symptoms:</p>=0A  =0A<p>Man=\ny people with cracked tooth syndrome have symptoms for months, but it's oft=\nen difficult to diagnose because the symptoms are not consistent.  You may =\nexperience pain in the tooth when you bite or chew. However, it probably wi=\nll not happen all the time. The tooth may be painful only when you bite in =\na specific way. You will not feel a constant ache, as you would if you had =\na toothache, but the tooth may be more sensitive to cold temperatures. One =\nparticularly telling symptom is pain upon release of biting.</p>=0A=0A<p>Di=\nagnosis:</p>=0A<p>Dr. Boyd will do a thorough examination of your mouth and=\n teeth, focusing on the tooth in question. He may use an instrument to feel=\n for cracks in the tooth and will inspect the gums around the tooth for irr=\negularities. Dr. Boyd may also use a special instrument to test the tooth f=\nor fractures. One instrument looks like a toothbrush without bristles that =\nfits over one part of the tooth at a time as you bite down. If you feel pai=\nn, the cusp being tested most likely has a crack affecting it. Your dentist=\n may shine a fiber-optic light on the tooth or stain it with a special dye =\nto search for a crack. If the tooth already has a filling or crown, your de=\nntist may remove it so he or she can better inspect the tooth.</p>=0A=0A<p>=\nTreatment:</p>=0A<p>Treatments for cracked tooth syndrome do not always com=\npletely relieve the symptoms.=0ATreatment depends on the location, directio=\nn and extent of the crack. Cracks vary from superficial ones in the outer l=\nayers of the tooth to deep splits in the root affecting the pulp (the cente=\nr of the tooth, which contains the tooth's nerves). If the crack affects on=\ne or more cusps of a tooth, the tooth may be restored with a crown or onlay=\n. If a crack affects the pulp, you probably will need root canal treatment.=\n About 20% of teeth with cracked tooth syndrome require root canals. After =\na root canal, the tooth will no longer be sensitive to temperature, but it =\nstill will respond to pressure. This means that if you felt pain when you b=\nit down before the root canal, you probably will not feel it as intensely a=\ns before, but you may feel it from time to time. In some severe cases, the =\ntooth may need to be extracted. Some cracks extend into the root of the too=\nth under the bone and there's no way to fix the tooth. If your dentist deci=\ndes the tooth needs to be extracted, you can have it replaced with an impla=\nnt or a bridge.</p>=0A\t</div>=0A=0A\t<div id=3D\"Halitosis\" style=3D\"display:=\n none;\">=0A\t\t<p>Bad breath can be caused by foods such as garlic or onions,=\n tooth decay, periodontal (gum) disease, continued mouth dryness, use of to=\nbacco products, sinus or respiratory infections, some medical disorders (e.=\ng. diabetes), inadequate oral hygiene, or some medications. </p>=0A        =\n<p>In most cases, bad breath is caused by bacterial breakdown products call=\ned volatile sulfur compounds (VSCs). In people with healthy teeth and gums,=\n bacteria that live on the far back region of the tongue produce the VSCs. =\nIf the back of the tongue is the source of the halitosis, a tongue scraper =\nor toothbrush used on the tongue may help to remove the odor-causing bacter=\nia. </p>=0A        <p>In people with periodontal disease, bacteria reside i=\nn pockets on the roots of teeth beneath the gums. It is of great importance=\n to clean these area by regularly flossing and brushing, as well as receivi=\nng regular dental cleanings. Ask your hygienist and/or Dr. Boyd about metho=\nds to reduce or eliminate bad breath. </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Impl=\nants\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A            <img src=3D\"_images/procedure=\n_02Before.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"160\" />=0A            <img src=3D\"_i=\nmages/procedure_02After.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"160\" />=0A=0A\t\t<p>An i=\nmplant is a titanium screw placed in the jaw bone into which another screw =\ncan go. Essentially, the titanium screw replaces the root of a tooth. If yo=\nu are missing a tooth, an implant may be the best way to replace it conside=\nring that implants have a success rate of greater than 90%.</p>=0A        <=\np> If Dr. Boyd decides that an implant is the best option, he will confer w=\nith another specialist (either a periodontist or an oral surgeon) who will =\nthen place the implant. Usually, 3-6 months are needed to allow the bone to=\n heal around the implant before a crown can be placed on it.</p>=0A        =\n<p> This is the phase of treatment that Dr. Boyd will perform. It is import=\nant to remember that the charge for the connector to the implant is separat=\ne from the crown. </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Inlays\" style=3D\"display=\n: none;\">=0A            <img src=3D\"_images/procedure_06Before.jpg\" width=\n=3D\"248\" height=3D\"200\" />=0A            <img src=3D\"_images/procedure_06Af=\nter.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"200\" />=0A=0A\t\t<p>When too much tooth stru=\ncture has been lost or there has been a fracture in a tooth, a larger resto=\nration may be needed. Gold is the best material for inlays (smaller) and on=\nlays (bigger) due to certain properties of the metal which enable it to be =\nstrong but kind to opposing natural teeth and keep teeth from fracturing fu=\nrther.</p>=0A        <p> Porcelain can sometimes be used in cases where est=\nhetics is of the utmost importance. However, porcelain is a brittle materia=\nl that can fracture or wear away opposing natural teeth. </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=\n=0A\t<div id=3D\"Invisalign\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A\t\t<p>Invisalign=E2=\n=84=A2 is a way of straightening teeth without metallic braces. Instead, cl=\near acrylic shells (like a night/mouthguard) are worn all the time (except =\nwhen eating) and slowly move the teeth into proper alignment. Every two wee=\nks, a new shell will be given to you by Dr. Boyd, until you have reached th=\ne intended result.</p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"PartialDentures\" style=\n=3D\"display: none;\">=0A\t\t<p>A partial denture replaces several missing teet=\nh in one arch. Usually, a partial denture replaces both the teeth and the g=\nums in those areas where teeth have been lost. </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div i=\nd=3D\"Periodontal\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A            <img src=3D\"_imag=\nes/gumdisease.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"175\" />=0A=0A\t\t<p>Periodontal Di=\nsease is the loss of the bone support around teeth. There are certain bacte=\nria which live in and around the teeth in the periodontal pockets that chem=\nically cause the body to resorb bone around those infected teeth.</p>=0A   =\n     <p> Reducing the number, altering the kinds of bacteria, and limiting =\nthe amount of their food source is the best treatment for the disease. This=\n entails regular cleanings, proper oral hygiene (i.e. brushing and flossing=\n), and proper diagnosis. In some patients, medium-sized pockets can be trea=\nted with Arestin=E2=84=A2, a local antibiotic, to help eliminate the bacter=\nia in conjuntion with cleanings.</p>=0A        <p>In our office, we offer 3=\n different types of cleanings. For patients with a healthy mouth with no bo=\nne loss, our hygienists perform Preventive Care Therapy (diagnosis: healthy=\n=E2=80=941  visit cleaning).  For patients with gingivitis, they perform Pr=\neventive Periodontal Therapy (diagnosis: gingivitis=E2=80=94multiple visits=\n).</p>=0A        <p>  The multiple visits allow us to remove all pathogens =\nfrom around the teeth and make sure that the gingivitis gets reversed.  If =\nit is not, it could progress to periodontal disease which is no longer reve=\nrsible.  For patients who have lost bone support around their teeth (period=\nontal disease), we perform Non-surgical Periodontal Therapy (diagnosis: per=\niodontal disease=E2=80=94multiple visits). </p>=0A        <p> If patients d=\no not respond well enough to this last line of therapy, they may be referre=\nd to a periodontist, who specializes in the treatment of periodontal diseas=\ne, for evaluation and/or treatment.</p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Porcela=\nin\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A           <img src=3D\"_images/procedure_01=\nBefore.png\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"114\" />=0A           <img src=3D\"_image=\ns/procedure_01After.png\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"114\" />=0A\t\t<p>In order to=\n improve the appearance of your smile, you might consider porcelain veneers=\n (laminates). Veneers are shells of porcelain that cover the outside of the=\n tooth and can correct not only misshapen or dark teeth, but even teeth tha=\nt are poorly aligned. It is always best to whiten the teeth before cosmetic=\n procedures like this one. The procedure typically takes two visits with ab=\nout one to two weeks in between. In the first visit, a very small amount of=\n tooth structure is removed and the teeth have temporary veneers placed. In=\n the second visit after the case has returned from the lab, the permanent v=\neneers are cemented. Click here to see before-and-after pictures of porcela=\nin veneers. </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Post\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=\n=0A\t\t<p>After root canal therapy has been performed, if a lot of tooth stru=\ncture has been lost, a cast gold post and core will be required to give the=\n future crown something to fit around. The post end goes into the root(s) o=\nf the tooth; the core end acts to replace the lost tooth structure. At the =\nfirst visit, Dr. Boyd will prepare a space for the post down the root and t=\nake an impression. At the next visit the cast gold post will be cemented an=\nd the tooth will be prepared for the crown.  Click here to see photos of a =\npost and core </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Pregnancy\" style=3D\"display:=\n none;\">=0A\t\t<p>If you are pregnant or thinking about becoming pregnant, no=\nw is the time to pay particular attention to your teeth and gums.  That=E2=\n=80=99s because pregnancy=E2=80=94and the changing hormone levels that acco=\nmpany it=E2=80=94can exaggerate some dental problems.  Taking good care of =\nyour mouth during this time is important not just for your own sake, but al=\nso for the developing baby.  Research indicates that the worse the conditio=\nn of your gums, the greater the chance of having a low-birth weight, pre-te=\nrm baby.=0AMany women who previously had healthy gums may notice that their=\n gums become swollen or bleed during their pregnancy.  This condition is so=\nmetimes called =E2=80=9Cpregnancy gingivitis.=E2=80=9D  The rising hormone =\nlevels exaggerate the way your body reacts to irritants in plaque.  But rem=\nember, it=E2=80=99s plaque, not hormones, that is the major cause of gum di=\nsease.  You can prevent gingivitis by keeping your teeth clean, especially =\naround the gumline.  Dr. Boyd may recommend more frequent cleanings during =\nyour second or early third trimester to help control your gingivitis.=0AIf =\nyou are planning a pregnancy, it is a good idea to schedule an evaluation w=\nith Dr. Boyd.  Having your teeth examined and cleaned before your pregnancy=\n can help reduce the risk of having a dental emergency during your pregnanc=\ny.  Continue all regular dental visits throughout the 40 weeks.  Non-emerge=\nncy treatment can be performed safely during this time.  However, you may b=\ne advised to postpone elective treatment during the first three months.=0AW=\ne avoid taking radiographs (x-rays) on women who are, or may be, pregnant. =\n If, however, a radiograph is needed for a dental emergency that cannot wai=\nt until the baby is born, every precaution will be taken to minimize radiat=\nion exposure=0A</p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Premedication\" style=3D\"dis=\nplay: none;\">=0A\t\t<p>Patients with certain preexisting conditions may requi=\nre \"antibiotic prophylaxis.\" This involves taking an antibiotic 1 hour befo=\nre certain dental treatments in order to prevent the possibility of bacteri=\na growing on the valves of the heart, known as \"bacterial endocarditis.\" If=\n you have a condition (listed below) which requires antibiotic prophylaxis =\nor think you may, Dr. Boyd may confer with your physician on how best to ma=\nnage your particular situation.</p>=0A        <p>To learn more about antibi=\notic prophylaxis and the links between dental health and heart disease, cli=\nck here http://www.americanheart.org/presenter.jhtml?identifier=3D3047083 t=\no visit the American Heart Association's web page. </p>=0A<p>According to A=\nmerican College of Cardiology and the American Heart Association guidelines=\n, Antibiotic prophylaxis with dental procedures is reasonable only for pati=\nents with cardiac conditions associated with the highest risk of adverse ou=\ntcomes from endocarditis, including:</p>=0A=0A<p>&bull;Prosthetic cardiac v=\nalve or prosthetic material used in valve repair</p>=0A<p>&bull;Previous ba=\ncterial endocarditis</p>=0A<p>Congenital heart disease only in the followin=\ng categories:</p>=0A<p>&bull;Unrepaired cyanotic congenital heart disease, =\nincluding those with palliative shunts and conduits</p>=0A<p>&bull;Complete=\nly repaired congenital heart disease with prosthetic material or device, wh=\nether placed by surgery or catheter intervention, during the first six mont=\nhs after the procedure</p>=0A<p>&bull;Repaired congenital heart disease wit=\nh residual defects at the site or adjacent to the site of a prosthetic patc=\nh or prosthetic device (which inhibit endothelialization)</p>=0A<p>&bull;Ca=\nrdiac transplantation recipients with cardiac valvular disease</p>=0A=0A\t</=\ndiv>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Prosthodontics\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A        =\n <img src=3D\"_images/procedure_03Before.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"160\" />=\n=0A         <img src=3D\"_images/procedure_03After.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=\n=3D\"160\" />=0A\t\t<p>Prosthodontics is the specialty in dentistry that is con=\ncerned with the more complicated work like full-mouth rehabilitation, dentu=\nres, partial dentures, placing crowns on implants, and cosmetic dentistry. =\nAcross the country, in order to specialize in prosthodontics, a rigorous th=\nree-year-residency is required after the four years of dental school.</p>=\n=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Root\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A    <img src=\n=3D\"_images/rootCanalXRay.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"175\" />=0A\t\t<p>When =\nthe nerve in a tooth is no longer alive, either from decay, fracture, or tr=\nauma, a root canal is needed. Dr. Boyd will refer you to a specialist in th=\nis area called an Endodontist who will treat the tooth. In the specialist's=\n office, the tooth will be anesthetized and the canal in which the nerve li=\nes will be cleaned with tiny files and irrigated with antibacterial agents.=\n Then the endodontist will fill the canal with an inert, sterile material. =\nAfter this procedure you will most likely need a post and core and a crown.=\n </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div id=3D\"Toothache\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A  =\n           <img src=3D\"_images/tooth-ache.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"215\"=\n />=0A\t\t<p>There are many reasons why a tooth may be hurting you. It is imp=\nortant to come in and see Dr. Boyd as soon as you can once a tooth begins t=\no hurt. After a thorough exam, Dr. Boyd will diagnose the problem and take =\nsteps to take you out of pain. If you have a toothache after working hours,=\n please call the answering service at (212) 774-1485 and they will be able =\nto locate one of the doctors who can assist you. </p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t<div=\n id=3D\"ToothBleaching\" style=3D\"display: none;\">=0A             <img src=3D=\n\"_images/procedure_04Before.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"160\" />=0A        =\n     <img src=3D\"_images/procedure_04After.jpg\" width=3D\"248\" height=3D\"160=\n\" />=0A=0A\t\t<p>We have achieved the best whitening results using a combinat=\nion of in-office Zoom!=E2=84=A2, followed by two weeks of at-home whitening=\n trays and gel, followed by another round of in-office Zoom!=E2=84=A2.  The=\nre is one fee for this comprehensive service and our administrative team wo=\nuld be happy to discuss that with you.=0A        Zoom!=E2=84=A2 in-office t=\nooth-whitening is a procedure that lightens teeth an average of 8 shades us=\ning a combination of a hydrogen peroxide gel and a specially designed ultra=\nviolet lamp.  The lamp accelerates the results of the gel and allows maximu=\nm results in a shorter time.  During the entire treatment, a plastic retrac=\ntor will be placed in the mouth to keep the lips, cheeks and tongue away fr=\nom the teeth and the mouth open.  A light-cured barrier and gauze will be p=\nlaced over the gums and maybe even parts of the teeth to shield them from t=\nhe light and the gel.  Lip balm with SPF and UV-protective eyewear will be =\nused as well.  The teeth will be exposed to the light with the peroxide gel=\n for three (3), 15-minute sessions.=0A=0AThere are two kinds of sensitivity=\n associated with the procedure, the first of which is gum-sensitivity.  Thi=\ns can occur if some of the gel gets under the barriers if they become dislo=\ndged by excess movement.  This can result in a stinging sensation on the gu=\nms.  The second type of sensitivity is tooth-sensitivity.  This occurs when=\n the peroxide penetrates to the dentin layer of the tooth through microcrac=\nks.  It most frequently occurs in the lower front teeth and causes what we =\ncall =E2=80=9Czingers,=E2=80=9D which feel like short electric charges insi=\nde one tooth.  They most often go away within a few hours.  In very few peo=\nple, =E2=80=9Czingers=E2=80=9D last up to 24 hours and can be quite bothers=\nome.  Both kinds of sensitivity are short-lived and only occur in a small n=\number of cases.=0A=0ATo counteract sensitivity, we recommend that most peop=\nle take two to four ibuprofen or Advil=E2=84=A2 one hour prior to the proce=\ndure. In some cases, the trays that are used for at-home whitening can be u=\nsed with desensitizing agents.  Many people find that the worst part of the=\n procedure is boredom.  To address this, please feel free to bring your iPo=\nd=E2=84=A2 or video iPod=E2=84=A2 to listen to/watch your choice of materia=\nl.  If you should forget, we have an iPod=E2=84=A2 in the office with a lim=\nited musical selection.  Click here for some before and after photos of our=\n patients.=0A</p>=0A\t</div>=0A\t=0A\t</div> =0A\t<!-- END: DetailWrapper -->=\n=0A=0A<!-- End Index CENTER COLUMN --></div>=0A=0A=0A=0A\t<!-- This clearing=\n element should immediately follow the #mainContent div in order to force t=\nhe #container div to contain all child floats --><br class=3D\"clearfloat\" />=\n=0A<!-- end #container --></div>=0A</body>=0A</html>=0A<!-- text below gene=\nrated by server.
